{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3431c512-9852-4ec2-a021-d5701663be39","content":"Use the standard `--filter` option with `dotnet test`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThis matches any test whose fully qualified name contains `SmsNotificationTests`, which will run both `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ab7e7868-d972-4903-98e5-2860877c69a2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"TUnit uses its own test adapter. To filter by class name in TUnit, you use the `--treenode-filter` option, which is TUnit's native filtering mechanism. The filter syntax for class name would be something like `/**/*.SmsNotificationTests/*`.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit supports `--filter` (the standard dotnet test filter) as well as `--treenode-filter`. \n\nFor standard dotnet test filtering, you'd use:\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nOr with the class filter:\n\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName=Contoso.Notifications.Tests.SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nBoth approaches work with TUnit, though the standard `--filter` option is simpler and more straightforward.","outputTokens":366,"requestId":"3409:1E3288:AA14AB:C82FE3:69F40219"},"id":"1e2c7667-88bd-495a-8ac3-1c476d4a8c6a","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:30:14.131Z","parentId":"ad49bd31-0aa1-45c3-be63-0ab2311dcfcd"}
